@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(vi) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it binds a CLOSURE (`fn x -> x + 1`) and applies it — a value the
-- compute spine has no representation for yet (a lambda lowers to nothing, and a call
-- through a locally-bound name is not a `def`). The differential harness must report
-- it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier — never a miscompile,
-- never a JS crash.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists — built, element-read (`xs[i]`),
-- and measured (`length`/`isEmpty`) (see compile_list_test). The frontier now sits at
-- CLOSURES-AS-VALUES — a `fn x -> …` bound and called. This file binds one, so it
-- still refuses; when closures lower (a later D1 slice), it flips from `unsupported`
-- to a print with no edit.

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  let inc = fn x -> x + 1
  println(inc(5))
